[~] 2.  DEPENDENCIES (enumerate now; install via uv)
    [x] 2.1.  Runtime (required):
        [x] 2.1.1.  mcp — the official MCP Python SDK; bundles FastMCP.
                    Import: `from mcp.server.fastmcp import FastMCP`.
                    Pinned `mcp>=1.2` (resolved 1.28.0).
        [x] 2.1.2.  Python >= 3.10 (FastMCP requirement) — requires-python set.
        [x] 2.1.3.  Version read at runtime from package metadata via
                    importlib.metadata (stdlib) — NO extra dep. Wired in §4.3.
        [x] 2.1.4.  The skeleton's one tool (info) needs NOTHING beyond the
                    above. The GNU units ENGINE is a FUTURE dependency, not the
                    skeleton's — decide it in 2.4, wire it after section 9.
        [x] 2.1.5.  json-repair — pure-Python, zero-dep; the one extra runtime
                    dep, for the LLM-mangled-JSON tolerance wiring (§4.6).
                    Pinned `json-repair>=0.30` (resolved via lock).
    [x] 2.1.6.  FIXED-POINT NUMERIC CORE — ✅ DECIDED (2026-06-19): NO new dep.
                    The engine (§2.4 / FUTURE) needs fixed-point arithmetic that
                    also computes the number of decimals actually required and
                    labels each result exact vs inexact — the same numeric model
                    mcp-abacus exposes. Abacus does this with the Python STDLIB
                    ONLY: `decimal.Decimal` + `decimal.localcontext` (fixed-point
                    / exact-scaled-integer + per-op precision / rounding readout),
                    `fractions.Fraction` (exact rational), and `math` for floats.
                    Its sole external deps are `mcp` + `json-repair` — BOTH already
                    in our plan (§2.1.1, §2.1.5) — so the fixed-point math adds
                    NOTHING to dependencies.
                    POLICY: align with mcp-abacus's DEPENDENCY CHOICES where
                    feasible (stay on stdlib decimal/fractions; same mcp +
                    json-repair floors), but DO NOT share or copy mcp-abacus CODE
                    — we re-implement our own numeric core for the units engine.
                    Treat ../mcp-abacus as a READ-ONLY reference for the approach
                    (see its src/mcp_abacus/expr/value.py for the exact/inexact +
                    rounded-to-N-decimals verdict pattern), not a code source.
    [x] 2.2.  Dev / tooling:
        [x] 2.2.1.  uv — env, dependency resolution, lockfile (uv.lock generated
                    via `uv sync --extra dev`).
        [x] 2.2.2.  pytest — test runner (dev extra: pytest>=8.0).
        [ ] 2.2.3.  pytest-asyncio — NOT added (info() is sync; add lazily only
                    if a future tool is async).
        [x] 2.2.4.  ruff — lint + format (dev extra: ruff>=0.6; `ruff check` green).
        [x] 2.2.5.  mypy — optional static typing (dev extra: mypy>=1.11; configured).
    [x] 2.3.  Build backend: hatchling.
    [x] 2.4.  ENGINE — ✅ DECIDED (2026-06-19): SHIP A COPY of the GNU units
              database and parse it with OUR OWN pure-Python parser. NO reliance
              on a system `units(1)` binary.
              WHY (chosen over the subprocess approach): works cross-platform
              (Windows / macOS / Linux — no PATH or install dependency), faster
              (no process spawn per call), fully offline + genuinely deterministic
              (we PIN the DB version, so the frozen description's "deterministic"
              claim is now unconditionally true), and we own the engine. Bonus:
              no subprocess ⇒ no shell-injection / file-include / `!`-define
              attack surface to defend.
              OBLIGATIONS / NOTES:
                - Ship the data at e.g. src/mcp_gnu_units/data/definitions.units
                  and FORCE-INCLUDE it in the wheel (§3.5) — it is PACKAGE DATA,
                  not importable code.
                - PIN + record the upstream DB version shipped (e.g. GNU units
                  2.27 definitions.units, 2026-04-01); surface it from info()
                  (§5.4); document provenance in README.
                - LICENSE: definitions.units is GPL-3.0-or-later © FSF — ship it
                  VERBATIM with its copyright header intact, add a NOTICE crediting
                  GNU units / the FSF, reference it from the README homage
                  (§10.5.2). Our code is GPLv3 too ⇒ wholly compatible.
                - The PARSER is its own real piece of work (FUTURE): the units
                  grammar has base + derived units, SI/binary prefixes, nonlinear
                  units (tempC/tempF, dB) defined via functions, piecewise defs,
                  and `!`/`!include` directives. Scope + validate it there.
                - Pure-Python ⇒ NO new runtime dep for the engine (json-repair
                  from §2.1.5 stays the only extra).


