================================================================================
THE FINAL DESCRIPTION  (searchable / discoverability-tuned — LOCK BEFORE INDEX)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
⚠️ Glama FREEZES the search description at first index (§12.0); the PyPI summary
and the pyproject `description` are the SAME string. Use the PRIMARY line
verbatim as pyproject.toml `description` AND `gh repo edit --description`; use the
LONG form as the README first paragraph (becomes the Glama Overview body).

Discoverability rule (the mcp-abacus lesson): LEAD with the words people actually
SEARCH — "unit converter", "convert units", "unit conversion", "measurement" —
not a clever phrase nobody types. THEN pack the distinctive, uncontested keywords
("GNU units", "unit expression", "SI base units", "dimensional") + concrete
category names. Stays consistent with the 5 shipped tools (convert,
convert_to_si, find_units, define_unit, list_prefixes) — no currency, no
conformable claims.

PRIMARY  (pyproject `description` = PyPI summary = Glama FROZEN search text):
  "Unit converter powered by the GNU units database — convert between 3000+
   units of measurement, evaluate compound unit expressions, reduce quantities
   to SI base units, and look up unit definitions. Offline and deterministic."

GITHUB repo description  (shorter, same lead word):
  "Unit conversion MCP server powered by the GNU units database: convert 3000+
   units, evaluate unit expressions, reduce to SI base units. Offline."

LONG  (README first paragraph = Glama Overview body):
  "mcp-gnu-units is an MCP server that gives AI agents precise, offline unit
   conversion backed by the GNU units database. Convert between 3000+ units of
   measurement — length, mass, time, temperature, area, volume, energy, power,
   pressure, speed, data and more — evaluate compound unit expressions like
   `kW*h` or `acre*ft`, reduce any quantity to its SI base units, search the unit
   database by keyword, and look up the exact definition of any unit, prefix, or
   physical constant. Deterministic, dimension-aware, and free of the hardcoded
   per-category unit tables every other converter ships."

pyproject `keywords`:
  ["units", "unit-conversion", "unit-converter", "convert", "measurement",
   "gnu-units", "dimensional-analysis", "si-units", "metric", "imperial"]
================================================================================


================================================================================
FUTURE (NOT PART OF THE SKELETON) — domain tool surface for the units engine
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Recorded from the 2026-06-19 Glama research so the plan isn't lost. Build these
ONLY after section 9 is green. ~5 tools — leaner than the category leader's 15,
but each far more powerful (one `convert` covers every category plus compound
units), and unit-expression evaluation plus database search/define are
capabilities NO competitor on Glama provides:

  ENGINE (build FIRST — every tool depends on it): a pure-Python PARSER +
  evaluator for the bundled definitions.units DB (§2.4). Parse base + derived
  units, SI/binary prefixes, nonlinear units (tempC/tempF, dB) + piecewise defs,
  and `!`/`!include` directives; reduce any expression to base dimensions; check
  conformability internally; format output. VALIDATE it against real GNU `units`
  outputs as a test oracle (golden tests below).

  NUMERICS (§2.1.6): evaluate conversions in FIXED-POINT and report how many
  decimals are actually needed, labelling each result exact vs inexact — the
  mcp-abacus numeric model. Use stdlib only: `decimal.Decimal` +
  `decimal.localcontext` (scale + per-op rounding/precision readout) and
  `fractions.Fraction` for exact ratios; NO new dep. Re-implement our own core —
  do NOT import/copy mcp-abacus code; ../mcp-abacus/src/mcp_abacus/expr/value.py
  is a READ-ONLY reference for the exact/inexact + rounded-to-N-decimals verdict.

  convert            Convert a value or unit expression from one unit to another
                     (e.g. "2.5 acre*ft" -> gallons); universal core that
                     replaces all per-category tools.
  convert_to_si      Reduce a unit expression to SI base units / a magnitude
                     (e.g. "kW*h" -> joules).
  find_units         Search/grep the GNU units database by name or keyword.
  define_unit        Show a unit / prefix / physical-constant definition,
                     dimensionality, and base value.
  list_prefixes      Enumerate SI / binary prefixes with their multipliers.
  (info)             Extend the skeleton's info() to also report engine/database
                     version.

TESTS for the domain tools (extend §7): beyond the info-only skeleton tests, add
GOLDEN conversion assertions that pin known answers (e.g. 1 mi -> 1.609344 km;
0 degC -> 32 degF; 1 kW*h -> 3.6e6 J; an inconvertible pair errors cleanly) to
catch parser regressions — ideally generated by diffing OUR parser's output
against the real GNU `units` binary across a sample of the DB (oracle test; the
binary is a DEV/test dependency only, never shipped or called at runtime).
Per-tool + per-parameter descriptions also directly
feed Glama's Tool-Definition-Quality grade, so write them richly ("schema
coverage 0%" is the common ding).
